Name: Reuter's Commodity Index
Metadata: This index includes 17 primary commodities weighted by their relative importance in international trade, and is a geometric average of the spot prices of the underlying commodities, using price quotations in Britain, Rotterdam, Hamburg and Antwerp. The base is September 18, 1931 = 100. The index includes only staple commodities (no energy or precious metals), and weights reflect pre-World War II trading patterns.  Its components include wheat (14%), cotton (13%), coffee (11%), wool (11%), copper (9%), sugar (7%), rubber (7%), maize/corn (5%), rice (4%), beef (4%), soybeans (3%), cocoa (3%), tin (2%), ground nut oil (2%), copra (2%), zinc (1%) and lead (1%). The most recent revision to the index came on December 6, 1995 when the components were changed to energy (crude oil, heating oil and natural gas) 17.6%, grains (wheat, corn, soybeans) 17.6%, industrials (copper, cotton) 11.8%, meats (live cattle, lean hogs) 11.8%, softs (coffee, cocoa, sugar, orange juice) 23.5% and precious metals (gold, silver, platinum) 17.6%.
